
# Distinguishing Daydreaming and Focused Attention Using Webcam-Based Eye Tracking

## Overview

This project investigates whether internally directed attention (IDA), such as daydreaming or mind-wandering, can be distinguished from externally directed attention (EDA), such as focused task engagement, using eye-related features captured through a standard webcam.

Unlike traditional attention-monitoring systems that rely on expensive hardware such as EEG devices or professional eye trackers, this system uses only a laptop webcam and computer vision techniques to extract eye-related behavioural features.

The project consists of two main components:

1. Model Training (train_loso.py)
2. Live Attention Prediction (eye_tracker_live_predict.py)

---

# Research Objective

The goal of this project is to determine whether the following eye-related features can be used to classify attention states:

- Blink Frequency
- Gaze Movement / Gaze Dispersion
- Pupil Size

The system attempts to classify users into one of two categories:

| Label | Attention State |
|---------|---------|
| 0 | Focused (External Attention) |
| 1 | Daydreaming (Internal Attention) |

